{
  "answer": "**The speaker portrays their \"secret occupation\" as the masterful, hidden art of \"feasting on sorrow\" (or enduring grief stealthily), along with a series of other skills related to silent suffering in love.**[^1]\n\nThis ghazal's opening couplet establishes the theme—\"To feast on sorrow, hide the strain—an art I know\"—with every subsequent couplet repeating \"an art I know\" to describe feats like weeping internally like rain, feigning praise amid pain, or smiling through heartbreak.[^2] It's a poetic metaphor for stoic mastery of romantic torment, not a literal job.\n\n[^1]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, chapter 12, \"Chupke chupke gham ka khana koi hum se seekh jaaye\" (translation), [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/12-chupke-chupke-gham-ka-khana-koi-hum-se-seekh-jaaye/translation/#p-f1ef29).\n\n[^2]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, chapter 12 (full chapter, translation), [/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/12-chupke-chupke-gham-ka-khana-koi-hum-se-seekh-jaaye/translation/].",
